Polish nobles and magnates
enjoyed limitless privileges

7
00:00:41,680 --> 00:00:45,960
to the growing discontent of the
Cossack community, the Sietch.

8
00:00:46,280 --> 00:00:50,800
Meanwhile the Crimean Tartars
started to threaten Europe...

9
00:02:51,200 --> 00:02:52,320
Dead?

10
00:02:52,680 --> 00:02:54,800
Alive, lieutenant.

11
00:02:55,360 --> 00:02:57,240
It's someone important.

12
00:02:58,920 --> 00:03:02,200
Beautiful horse. It's ours?

13
00:03:02,520 --> 00:03:04,960
- Rzêdzian!
- It's a trophy.

14
00:03:05,280 --> 00:03:06,400
Water!

15
00:03:12,840 --> 00:03:15,040
Set me free. I'll pay.

16
00:03:15,360 --> 00:03:17,400
Thank God we were nearby.

17
00:03:17,720 --> 00:03:20,840
- The rogues pretended
to be Tartars. - Of course.

18
00:03:21,160 --> 00:03:24,360
- You know him?
- My neighbor's servant.

19
00:03:27,080 --> 00:03:28,280
Thank you...

20
00:03:29,240 --> 00:03:30,440
for saving me.

21
00:03:30,760 --> 00:03:32,960
Am I dealing with a nobleman?

22
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:35,640
Yes. I'm Zenobius Abdank,

23
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:39,520
a colonel in the Cossack
regiment of prince Zas³awski.

24
00:03:39,840 --> 00:03:42,960
John Skrzetuski, lieutenant

25
00:03:43,280 --> 00:03:47,040
- at Prince Jeremy's service.
- He's a famous warrior.

26
00:03:48,440 --> 00:03:49,640
Thank you.

27
00:03:53,920 --> 00:03:55,200
What's the rush?

28
00:03:56,200 --> 00:04:00,040
Duty calls.
I'm carrying orders.

29
00:04:02,480 --> 00:04:04,440
It's a small world.

30
00:04:05,080 --> 00:04:06,200
Perhaps...

31
00:04:07,560 --> 00:04:10,080
I'll be able
to return this favor.

32
00:04:15,080 --> 00:04:18,520
Do you know
whom you really saved?

33
00:04:18,840 --> 00:04:21,720
I'm Bohdan Zenobius Chmielnicki.

